<font color="#FF0000">TEACHERS PLEASE READ</font><br>
<tt>Fri Feb 21 22:17:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Students &amp; Teachers,<br><br>
You have a choice when the Nam comes up. You teach the facts<br>
of documented history, and how it all came down and ended<br>
for history, or...<br><br>
Go back to Arthur's comment. If a teacher wants any lesson<br>
to be imparted to young students, bring in a Vet. Otherwise<br>
it's just history class being passed.<br><br>
I have gone three times by invite to classes in High School.<br>
Three times since I left Nam in '69. Each of those might<br>
have been some of the most powerful moments I have ever had<br>
dealing with it, because when the War is actually in their<br>
face, kids dig in.<br><br>
It causes that special moment when young people are eager to<br>
learn. For Vets, it is sweet agony. The last thing we ever<br>
want is for everyone to forget, even though we know they<br>
will when we are all gone. It will be a footnote in history.<br><br>
How I wish as a kid I could have had a Vet of say the Civil<br>
War in my classroom for one hour. What an insight and what<br>
an impact it would have had. Try it, teachers. The window<br>
is getting short.<br><br>
We were the future as kids, young people. We got the Nam. <br>
It's important that we give of ourselves because as sad as<br>
it seems sometimes, it may be the most important thing we<br>
can give.<br><br>
Many won't do it. But many will. Living breathing history<br>
gets thier attention.<br><br>
See you back in the World.<br>

